	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
			<p>With the help of God&#8212;<date>Wednesday&#44; 15 Shevat<lb/> 1865</date>&#44;
					<placeName>Savannah</placeName>&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Peace&#44; blessings&#44; and good fortune to<lb/> God&#39;s friend
				and my own&#44; the doer of<lb/> righteousness&#44; his honor&#44; our teacher and<lb/>
				<persName>rabbi Isaac Hzik</persName>&#44; may his light burn brightly.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your letter of the <date>27<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of Tebeth</date>
				<del>is at</del><lb/>
				<del>hand&#44;</del> came into my hands&#44; and I rejoiced<lb/> greatly. As to
					<persName>Madam Goldschmid</persName>&#44; I be&#45;<lb/>lieve that if you were
				as well acquainted<lb/> with her character as I&#44; you would never<lb/> have sent
				her a Bible. I marvel that<lb/> she returned the same to you. Nevertheless&#44;<lb/>
				in order to do his bidding I went to her<lb/> home&#44; and this is what she said.
				She wanted<lb/> a small Bible <del>with</del> in large type&#44; but
				inexpensive<lb/> and then&#44; I believe&#44; not to pay for it.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">As to the man whose name is <persName>Bick</persName>&#44;<lb/> that
				in Polish &#34;ox&#34;&#44; is like his name<lb/> a goring ox. I have not spoken to
				him<lb/> in many months&#44; and he is now more<lb/> peaceful. During the past month
				of <date>Ab</date>&#44; when he</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
			<p>left for the <placeName>north</placeName>&#44; he told me that he would<lb/> purchase
				for himself a Bible when in your<lb/> town. He returned home and brought
					<del>these</del><lb/> two. He told me that the one for &#36;12 <del>are</del> is
				to be sent to <persName>Mr. Dessauer</persName> in <placeName>Macon</placeName>
				for<lb/> a man whose name is <persName>Krau</persName><del>n</del>. I sent<lb/> them
				to <persName>Mr. Krau</persName> himself&#44; and when I was<lb/> there
					<persName>Mr. Krau</persName> told me that he had not<lb/> ordered any.
				Nevertheless he kept them<lb/> and will pay &#36;12 to <persName>Mr.
					Dessauer</persName>. Should<lb/> this not prove to be the case&#44; let me
				know<lb/> and I will collect it. &#40;The last three<lb/> ordered I have
				received&#41;. As to the second<lb/> copy it is in the possession of the Ox. I<lb/>
				could have sold it long ago. I sent <del>my</del> his<lb/> brother to him that he
				should return the<lb/> Bible. But he replied that if you wrote<lb/> to him to hand
				the Bible over to me&#44; he would<lb/> do so. I would advise you to write to<lb/>
				his brother whose name is <persName>Levy E. Bick</persName>.<lb/> For if you wrote
				to him directly&#44; I believe<lb/> I should never hear of it. Or&#44; write to<lb/>
				me directly. <date>15 Shevat 1865</date></p>
			<pb n="3"/>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I have nothing more that is new&#59;<lb/> except that last
					<date>Tuesday</date> I sent five<lb/> hundred dollars to the people of
					<placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>.<lb/> The money I sent them on last
					<date>Rosh<lb/> Hodesh Ellul</date> did not get to them till<lb/>
				<date>Rosh Hodesh Heshvan</date>. Certainly this<lb/> money just sent will reach
				them by<lb/>
				<date>Passover</date>&#44; and they will enjoy the holiday.<lb/> From <del>his</del>
				your friend and servant who<lb/> is ready to serve <del>him</del> you at all
				times</p>
			<p><persName role="author">Judah Leib Draabin</persName> &#40;&#63;&#41;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I delivered your letter to <persName>Mr. Eckman</persName>.<lb/> He thereupon wanted
				that I should take in<lb/> my care your books now lying in his store.<lb/> I said
				that if you commissioned me to do&#44;<lb/> I would do it with the greatest
				pleasure.<lb/> This week he told me that he had some money<lb/> to send you&#44; and
				that he would send it to you<lb/> this week. <persName>Mr. Einstein</persName> went
				to <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> this week. You will probably see him in<lb/>
				your city. <date>15 <sic>Sheval</sic> 1865</date> The above <add>&#63;</add></p>
		</body>
